where there's not much women.

00:35:17.770 --> 00:35:20.780
And you experienced a lot
of hardships along the way.

00:35:20.780 --> 00:35:24.630
Who did you confide in, and who
were your instrumental friends

00:35:24.630 --> 00:35:25.320
and confidantes?

00:35:25.320 --> 00:35:27.440
You mentioned that you
had a great mentor,

00:35:27.440 --> 00:35:30.880
as well, who was
it your squadron.

00:35:30.880 --> 00:35:33.890
And also, I wanted to find out
the second piece, which is,

00:35:33.890 --> 00:35:35.517
I think you're a Googler?

00:35:35.517 --> 00:35:36.100
I see a badge.

00:35:36.100 --> 00:35:36.510
LOREE DRAUDE: I am.

00:35:36.510 --> 00:35:37.080
Yeah.

00:35:37.080 --> 00:35:40.230
AUDIENCE: What led you, then,
to also decide to leave?

00:35:40.230 --> 00:35:41.660
LOREE DRAUDE: Yeah.

00:35:41.660 --> 00:35:46.740
So when I was in
the Navy, my parents

00:35:46.740 --> 00:35:51.060
were huge pillars of
support-- especially my dad

00:35:51.060 --> 00:35:54.500
because he had a long
career in the military.

00:35:54.500 --> 00:35:57.570
He knew what it was
like to lose people

00:35:57.570 --> 00:36:02.150
that you had served with
much more than I did.

00:36:02.150 --> 00:36:04.520
On my first deployment,
we lost like 11 people.

00:36:04.520 --> 00:36:07.410
It was a lot for a deployment.

00:36:07.410 --> 00:36:09.480
But as an infantry
officer in Vietnam,

00:36:09.480 --> 00:36:11.650
he had dealt with that
on a much bigger basis.

00:36:11.650 --> 00:36:13.440
So I think my parents
are definitely

00:36:13.440 --> 00:36:17.420
a huge-- they were
amazing for support.

00:36:17.420 --> 00:36:20.830
I had some friends, other
women that I had gone through

00:36:20.830 --> 00:36:22.510
with that were on
the ship with me,

00:36:22.510 --> 00:36:24.930
and they were also
great support.

00:36:24.930 --> 00:36:28.480
We would get together
and share experiences

00:36:28.480 --> 00:36:34.370
and commiserate sometimes, but
also help boost each other up.

00:36:34.370 --> 00:36:36.900
My squadron was also amazing.

00:36:36.900 --> 00:36:38.710
I had a couple of
different friends

00:36:38.710 --> 00:36:43.150
in my squadron that got
beyond their personal biases

00:36:43.150 --> 00:36:46.390
and were there to
help me be successful.

00:36:46.390 --> 00:36:49.756
So I think that
really helped as well.

00:36:49.756 --> 00:36:50.880
At the time, I was married.

00:36:50.880 --> 00:36:53.090
So my husband was
also in the military,

00:36:53.090 --> 00:36:55.110
and he could appreciate
what was happening.

00:36:55.110 --> 00:36:58.565
And so just having that support
back home was also helpful.

00:36:58.565 --> 00:37:00.190
So I had a really
good support network,

00:37:00.190 --> 00:37:01.898
and I think that's
one of the things that

00:37:01.898 --> 00:37:04.560
really helped me be successful.

00:37:04.560 --> 00:37:06.610
The second part about
why did I get out

00:37:06.610 --> 00:37:09.540
of the Navy, a couple
different things.

00:37:09.540 --> 00:37:11.940
I reached the point where
my commitment was up.

00:37:11.940 --> 00:37:14.000
So as a pilot, I had
to serve seven years

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:16.050
after I got my wings, and
it took me three years

00:37:16.050 --> 00:37:16.970
to get wings.

00:37:16.970 --> 00:37:20.095
This was back when we had
a lot of budget cutbacks,

00:37:20.095 --> 00:37:22.590
so it took awhile to get
through the training program.

00:37:22.590 --> 00:37:24.280
So by the time it was
all said and done,

00:37:24.280 --> 00:37:26.280
I could finally get out,
it was 10 years anyway.

00:37:26.280 --> 00:37:29.650
So I was weighing, OK, do I
stay in another 10 and retire,

00:37:29.650 --> 00:37:30.520
or do I get out?

00:37:30.520 --> 00:37:34.155
And there were a few
things about the military

00:37:34.155 --> 00:37:34.974
I did not like.

00:37:34.974 --> 00:37:36.640
I think having grown
up in the military,

00:37:36.640 --> 00:37:39.280
I was so used to being
told where to go and live

00:37:39.280 --> 00:37:40.160
and what to do.

00:37:40.160 --> 00:37:44.170
And I was like, I want to
go live in San Francisco.

00:37:44.170 --> 00:37:46.890
And I want to go
live here or there.

00:37:46.890 --> 00:37:50.750
And I want to travel
whenever I want to.

00:37:50.750 --> 00:37:52.290
I wanted more
control over my life.

00:37:52.290 --> 00:37:55.220
That was really the main reason.

00:37:55.220 --> 00:37:59.510
Secondary to that was, in
the Navy, if I stayed in,

00:37:59.510 --> 00:38:04.440
the jobs I would be doing would
be more desk jobs, more staff

00:38:04.440 --> 00:38:06.050
jobs, and I really liked flying.

00:38:06.050 --> 00:38:07.550
I really liked being
on the carrier.

00:38:07.550 --> 00:38:08.966
I wanted to do
more of that, and I

00:38:08.966 --> 00:38:10.900
knew that my options for
doing that were going

00:38:10.900 --> 00:38:13.787
to decrease the longer I was in.

00:38:13.787 --> 00:38:15.370
And I knew I wanted
to start a family.

00:38:15.370 --> 00:38:18.730
So I just have
the utmost respect

00:38:18.730 --> 00:38:20.840
for our military
service members who

00:38:20.840 --> 00:38:23.700
serve while having children.

00:38:23.700 --> 00:38:26.570
And I didn't know
if I could do that.

00:38:26.570 --> 00:38:28.153
I had two dogs when
I was in the Navy,

00:38:28.153 --> 00:38:29.652
and it was hard
enough leaving them.

00:38:29.652 --> 00:38:32.110
I was like, if I can't leave
my four-legged children,

00:38:32.110 --> 00:38:35.860
how am I going to leave
two-legged children?

00:38:35.860 --> 00:38:37.770
So all those things
came together

00:38:37.770 --> 00:38:40.830
and I decided to
leave the service.

00:38:40.830 --> 00:38:43.080
CELINE: I'll round out the
talk with the last question

00:38:43.080 --> 00:38:47.050
on, based on your experiences,
any learnings that you want

00:38:47.050 --> 00:38:50.369
to share with the
group or key takeaways?

00:38:50.369 --> 00:38:51.160
LOREE DRAUDE: Yeah.

00:38:51.160 --> 00:38:55.090
I think for me, what made
the biggest difference was

00:38:55.090 --> 00:38:59.880
leadership in the Navy, and
particularly in our air wing.

00:38:59.880 --> 00:39:03.040
We were the first air wing
in the Navy on the West Coast

00:39:03.040 --> 00:39:05.460
to deploy, but a few
months before we deployed,

00:39:05.460 --> 00:39:07.870
there was an air wing on the
East Coast that deployed.

00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:10.930
And they did not have any
of the issues that we had.

00:39:13.910 --> 00:39:19.800
A couple of the female
aviators were the top landers--

00:39:19.800 --> 00:39:20.860
we call them "Top Hook."

00:39:20.860 --> 00:39:24.250
It means that you have some
of the best landing grades.

00:39:24.250 --> 00:39:26.450
The women there felt supported.

00:39:26.450 --> 00:39:28.700
It was a very different
experience for the women

00:39:28.700 --> 00:39:32.810
on-- it was the "Eisenhower."

00:39:32.810 --> 00:39:36.220
In our air wing, it was
quite a bit different.

00:39:36.220 --> 00:39:38.884
So the first time
we deployed, they

00:39:38.884 --> 00:39:40.300
made us all take
a pregnancy test.

00:39:40.300 --> 00:39:41.758
So there was this
feeling like they

00:39:41.758 --> 00:39:43.400
didn't trust us to be ready.

00:39:43.400 --> 00:39:46.500
And there were just
many other things, too.

00:39:46.500 --> 00:39:50.224
And so I think having
strong leadership,

00:39:50.224 --> 00:39:52.515
that would've made a huge
difference for our deployment

00:39:52.515 --> 00:39:56.090
if we'd had better
leadership at the very top.

00:39:56.090 --> 00:39:59.020
Like I mentioned before, my
squadron commanding officer

00:39:59.020 --> 00:40:01.760
was wonderful, and that make
a huge difference for me.

00:40:01.760 --> 00:40:03.550
So I think you really
have to have leaders

00:40:03.550 --> 00:40:08.940
who make sure that the
culture supports that change.

00:40:08.940 --> 00:40:11.380
And then I would
also say what helped

00:40:11.380 --> 00:40:16.010
me was just being empathetic to
the other people I was serving

00:40:16.010 --> 00:40:17.770
with and what their
experience must

00:40:17.770 --> 00:40:23.390
have been like to have this huge
change really pushed on them.

00:40:23.390 --> 00:40:26.440
But then also for me being
put into that situation,

00:40:26.440 --> 00:40:29.760
how could we both be
respectful of the concerns

00:40:29.760 --> 00:40:31.440
we had about each other.

00:40:31.440 --> 00:40:32.820
I was worried that
I wasn't going

00:40:32.820 --> 00:40:34.570
to get a fair shake
because I was a woman,

00:40:34.570 --> 00:40:35.680
and they were
worried that I wasn't

00:40:35.680 --> 00:40:37.221
going to cut it
because I was a woman

00:40:37.221 --> 00:40:39.930
and maybe wasn't getting
the training I needed.

00:40:39.930 --> 00:40:42.010
So being empathetic.

00:40:42.010 --> 00:40:43.560
Then finally, humor.

00:40:43.560 --> 00:40:46.510
That got me through a lot.

00:40:46.510 --> 00:40:48.670
I think, especially, too,
with carrier aviation,

00:40:48.670 --> 00:40:51.520
it's literally life
and death environment.

00:40:51.520 --> 00:40:57.790
And I think because of that,
aviators tend to have, I think,

00:40:57.790 --> 00:41:01.360
a more wicked sense
of humor about things.

00:41:01.360 --> 00:41:03.087
So leadership,
empathy, and humor.

00:41:03.087 --> 00:41:03.670
CELINE: Great.

00:41:03.670 --> 00:41:05.680
Thank you, Loree, for your time.

00:41:05.680 --> 00:41:06.580
Happy Veteran's Day.

00:41:06.580 --> 00:41:09.330
